The Lagrangian module is a Fortran module plugged into the Ocean model Croco 
that allow to do particle tracking (in a Lagrangian framework).

The lagrangian module is inherited from the Model for Applications at Regional 
Scale (MARS 3D) developed at Ifremer (French Research Institute for the 
Exploitation of the Sea).

It computes the 3D transport by advection and diffusion of passive particles 
using a lagrangian approach online within CROCO. Transport can be chosen among 
fixed immersion (along a constant depth), advection only, and both advection 
and diffusion.

It can be used for a wide range of applications (physics and biology), from the 
2D transport of surface drifting buoys, to the 3D transport of pelagic stages 
of marine species such as early life stages (eggs a and larvae) of fish.

When more complex biological (and behaviour) processes need to be considered, 
the module FOIL (Fish Online IBM with Lagrangian) should be used, which calls 
the Lagrangian module for the passive transport.

Implementation in CROCO by : D.Gourves, M.Caillaud, M.Huret (2024-2026)